📝 Overview¶

This project examines health-related statistics and poverty levels across Michigan counties using public datasets from CDC PLACES and U.S. Census Bureau's American Community Survey. The goal is to uncover patterns in:

  • Health outcomes 🏥
  • Disabilities ♿
  • Risk behaviors 🚬🏃‍♂️
  • Socioeconomic factors 💰

By analyzing these factors, we aim to identify disparities and understand trends across different regions.

💡 Motivation¶

Health and economic conditions are deeply intertwined, influencing access to healthcare, disease prevalence, and overall well-being. By analyzing these datasets, we aim to explore how poverty correlates with various health indicators at the county level.

🔍 Real-World Questions¶

  1. How does the relationship between poverty rates and disease prevalence vary across U.S. counties, and do high-poverty areas experience significantly worse health outcomes compared to wealthier counties?

  2. What health risk behaviors are most prevalent in counties with higher poverty rates, and how do these behaviors correlate with disease prevalence?

  3. How do rural and urban counties differ in the impact of income on disease prevalence, and what specific diseases are most prevalent in these counties?

📊 Data Sources¶

🏥 1. CDC PLACES Health Data¶

  • URL: CDC PLACES
  • This dataset provides county-level health indicators, including disability prevalence, chronic conditions, and health-related behaviors.

📈 2. U.S. Census Bureau ACS 5-Year Estimates (Poverty and Median Income Data)¶

  • URL: Census ACS API
  • This api includes socioeconomic data such as poverty rates and income levels across different counties.

🎯 How These Datasets Complement Each Other¶

The CDC dataset provides detailed health-related statistics, while the Census American Community Survey dataset offers economic indicators such as poverty rates and household incomes. By combining them, we can analyze correlations between economic status and health outcomes, helping us identify trends and disparities across Michigan counties.

📊 Data Description¶

Our project focuses on the following key variables:

📌 CDC Places Health Dataset Variables (2022)¶

Although the current release of PLACES was published in 2024, it contains Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS) data from 2022/ 2021 against Census 5 year estimates.

  • Year – The year of data collection (e.g., 2022 (2021 for certain measures))
  • StateAbbr – Abbreviation of the state (e.g., FL for Florida)
  • StateDesc – Full name of the state
  • LocationName – County name
  • Category – Type of health indicator (e.g., Health Outcomes)
  • Measure – Detailed description of the health measure (e.g., "Arthritis among adults")
  • Data_Value_Unit – Unit of measurement (percentage in this case)
  • Data_Value_Type – Type of value, consists of crude and age-adjusted prevalence, but we're only taking age-adjusted prevalence
  • Data_Value – Percentage of the county population affected
  • TotalPopulation – Total population of the county
  • TotalPop18plus – Population of adults aged 18 and older
  • LocationID – Unique identifier for the location
  • CategoryID – Code representing the health indicator category
  • MeasureId – Code representing the specific health measure
  • Short_Question_Text – Short name of the health measure (e.g., "Obesity", "Stroke")

📌 Census ACS 5-Year Poverty Dataset Variables (2022)¶

  • Geography – Unique geographic identifier [GEO_ID]
  • Geographic Area Name – Name of the geographic area [NAME]
  • Total – Total population [S1701_C01_001E]
  • T_ Male – Total male population [S1701_C01_011E]
  • T_ Female – Total female population [S1701_C01_012E]
  • T_ African American – Total African American population [S1701_C01_014E]
  • T_ American Indian/Alaska Native – Total American Indian/Alaska Native population [S1701_C01_015E]
  • T_ Asian – Total Asian population [S1701_C01_016E]
  • T_ Hawaiian/ Pacific Islander – Total Hawaiian/Pacific Islander population [S1701_C01_017E]
  • T_ Two or more races – Total population of two or more races [S1701_C01_019E]
  • T_ Other race – Total population of other races [S1701_C01_018E]
  • T_ Hispanic or Latino – Total Hispanic or Latino population [S1701_C01_020E]
  • T_ White – Total White population [S1701_C01_021E]
  • BP_ Male – Below poverty male population [S1701_C02_011E]
  • BP_ Female – Below poverty female population [S1701_C02_012E]
  • BP_ African American – Below poverty African American population [S1701_C02_014E]
  • BP_ American Indian/Alaska Native – Below poverty American Indian/Alaska Native population [S1701_C02_015E]
  • BP_ Asian – Below poverty Asian population [S1701_C02_016E]
  • BP_ Hawaiian/ Pacific Islander – Below poverty Hawaiian/Pacific Islander population [S1701_C02_017E]
  • BP_ Two or more races – Below poverty population of two or more races [S1701_C02_019E]
  • BP_ Other race – Below poverty population of other races [S1701_C02_018E]
  • BP_ Hispanic or Latino – Below poverty Hispanic or Latino population [S1701_C02_020E]
  • BP_ White – Below poverty White population [S1701_C02_021E]
  • BP_ Total% – Below poverty White population [S1701_C02_021E]
  • T_Households – Total number of households [S1901_C01_001E]
  • Households<$10k – Number of households earning less than $10,000 [S1901_C01_002E]
  • Households>$200k – Number of households earning more than $200,000 [S1901_C01_011E]
  • Median income – Median household income [S1901_C01_012E]
  • Mean income – Mean (average) household income [S1901_C01_013E]

The dataset provides both state-wise and county-wise data. The Data_Value_Type consists of Age-adjusted prevalence alone, while the initial dataset had both Age-adjusted and Crude prevalence.

As Missouri Department of Health and Senior Services states:

Age adjusting rates allows fairer comparisons to be made between groups with different age distributions. For example, a county with a high percentage of elderly residents may have a higher rate of death or hospitalization than a county with a younger population, merely because the elderly are more likely to die or be hospitalized. (The same distortion can happen when comparing races, genders, or time periods.) Age adjustment can make the different geographies more comparable.

Therefore, we have decided to use Age-adjusted data. Immediately, Data_Value, Total_Population, Category, LocationName (County), and Measure immediately stand out for data visualization.

Data Processing¶

Since the Data_Value, which shows us the percentage of individuals affected by a particular health condition, is in percentage format, we need to obtain the actual number of people affected for our analysis. To do this, we create two new columns where values are stored as integers:

  1. TotalPatients: This column calculates the total number of individuals affected by the health condition across the entire population.

  2. TotalPatients18plus: This column calculates the number of individuals aged 18 and over affected by the health condition. The formula used is:

These new columns will allow us to work with counts of people, making our analysis easier to understand and enabling better comparisons across different locations and group types.

In [9]:
# Calculate the total number of patients based on the Data_Value and TotalPopulation
health_df['TotalPatients'] = (
    health_df['Data_Value'] * health_df['TotalPopulation'] / 100
).astype('int64')  # Convert the result to 'int64' type

# Calculate the total number of patients aged 18 and above based on the Data_Value and TotalPop18plus
health_df['TotalPatients18plus'] = (
    health_df['Data_Value'] * health_df['TotalPop18plus'] / 100
).astype('int64')  # Convert the result to 'int64' type

Data Visualization¶

In this section, we'll create a 2x3 subplot grid to visualize the total number of people affected by different health categories in Michigan. The categories are as follows:

  • Health Outcomes
  • Disability
  • Health Status
  • Prevention
  • Health-Related Social Needs
  • Health Risk Behaviors
In [14]:
# Define the list of categories to filter the data by
categories = ['Health Outcomes', 'Disability', 'Health Status', 'Prevention', 'Health-Related Social Needs', 'Health Risk Behaviors']  # Select categories for analysis

# Create a 2x3 grid of subplots to accommodate the six categories
fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize=(18, 12))
fig.suptitle("Health Data Analysis by Category", fontsize=16)

# Flatten the axes array to make iteration easier
axes = axes.flatten()

# Loop through each category to create a bar chart for each
for i, category in enumerate(categories):
    category_data = (
        michigan_df[michigan_df['Category'] == category] # Filter data for the current category
        .groupby('Short_Question_Text')['TotalPatients'] #Group by 'Short_Question_Text'
        .sum() #Sum 'TotalPatients'
        .sort_values(ascending=False)) #sort values in descending order
    
    # Create a bar plot for the current category
    sns.barplot(x=category_data.values, y=category_data.index, palette="magma", ax=axes[i])
    
    #Set the x-axis label and format the x-axis tick labels to prevent scientific notation
    axes[i].set_xlabel("Total People Affected")
    axes[i].ticklabel_format(style='plain', axis='x')
    
    #Set the y-axis label and title for the subplot
    axes[i].set_ylabel(category)
    axes[i].set_title(f"{category} by Total People Affected")
    
# Adjust the layout to prevent overlap of titles and labels
plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.1, 1, 0.98])

# Display the plots
plt.show()

We can infer and assume the following from the visualization:

  • The Health Outcomes category shows a higher number of people affected by conditions like obesity, high blood pressure, and high cholesterol. Wealth distribution could possibly play a crucial role in these outcomes, as individuals with lower income often face limited access to healthy food, exercise facilities, and healthcare services, which can exacerbate these chronic conditions.

  • The Disability category highlights significant numbers for cognitive disabilities and mobility disabilities. These disabilities may have a disproportionate impact on individuals in lower-income brackets, who may have less access to specialized care, rehabilitation, and assistive technologies.

  • The Health Status category reveals prevalent health issues such as frequent mental distress and general health concerns. Economic stress is a well-known contributor to mental health issues, and individuals in lower-income households may tend to experience financial instability, leading to increased levels of anxiety, depression, and other mental health challenges.

  • The Health-Related Social Needs category shows social isolation as the most affected issue. Wealth distribution is often linked to social networks, as individuals with lower income are more likely to experience social isolation due to living in less connected, underserved communities. Wealthier individuals may have better access to social spaces, professional networks, and community resources that can reduce social isolation, emphasizing how economic factors can shape social well-being.

We can explore our assumptions as we dive further into the poverty/ income data.

Disability Analysis in Michigan's Top 5 Most Populated Counties¶

Let’s identify the top 5 counties in Michigan with the highest total population by grouping the data by LocationName and summing the TotalPopulation. We will then filter the dataset to include only data related to Disability (excluding the Any Disability category, as that's the sum of all disabilities) and focus on the selected counties.

These two aggregates will be visualized in two bar charts:

  • The first chart will display the percentage of people affected by different types of disabilities in the top 5 most populated counties.
  • The second chart will show the total number of people affected by each disability type in these counties.

We are doing this step to determine whether percentage or the total patient population is better for visualization purposes.

In [15]:
# Identify the top 5 counties with the largest total population
top_counties = michigan_df.groupby("LocationName")["TotalPopulation"].sum().nlargest(5).index

# Filter the DataFrame for data related to the "Disability" category
top_county_data = michigan_df[
    (michigan_df["Category"] == "Disability") &  #Filter for Disability category
    (michigan_df["Short_Question_Text"] != "Any Disability") &  # Exclude "Any Disability"
    (michigan_df["LocationName"].isin(top_counties))  #Filter for top 5 counties
]

# Group the filtered data by 'Short_Question_Text' and 'LocationName', 
# sum 'Data_Value' (percentage), and unstack the data to create a matrix format
disability_percentage = (
    top_county_data.groupby(["Short_Question_Text", "LocationName"])["Data_Value"]
    .sum()
    .unstack()  # Convert 'LocationName' to columns
    .fillna(0)  # Replace missing values with 0
)

# Similarly, group by 'Short_Question_Text' and 'LocationName', 
# sum 'TotalPatients' (total people affected), and unstack the data
disability_total = (
    top_county_data.groupby(["Short_Question_Text", "LocationName"])["TotalPatients"]
    .sum()
    .unstack()  # Convert 'LocationName' to columns
    .fillna(0)  #replace missing values with 0
)

# Create a 1x2 grid of subplots for visualizing the data
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(20, 8))

# First plot: Bar plot showing the percentage of people affected by different disabilities
disability_percentage.plot(kind="barh", colormap="viridis", ax=axes[0])
axes[0].set_xlabel("Percentage Affected")  # Label for the x-axis
axes[0].set_ylabel("Disability Type")  # Label for the y-axis
axes[0].set_title("Disability Type by Percent Affected in Top 5 Populated Counties")  # Title for the plot

# Second plot: Bar plot showing the total number of people affected by different disabilities
disability_total.plot(kind="barh", colormap="viridis", ax=axes[1])
axes[1].set_xlabel("Total People Affected")  # Label for the x-axis
axes[1].set_ylabel("Disability Type")  # Label for the y-axis
axes[1].set_title("Disability Type by Total People Affected in Top 5 Populated Counties")  # title for the plot

# Adjust the layout to prevent overlap of titles and labels
plt.tight_layout()

# Display the plots
plt.show()

We can infer the following:

  • Percentage of People Affected: The first chart, showing the percentage of the population affected by different disabilities, reveals that mobility disabilities and cognitive disabilities are the most common conditions, with significant proportions of the population in these counties affected. Wayne County has the highest percentage, while Oakland County has the lowest percentage of individuals affected.

  • Total Number of People Affected: The second chart, displaying the total number of people affected by disabilities, highlights counties with larger populations, which somewhat skews the results. For example, although mobility disabilities affect a significant percentage of people, this chart doesn't account for population size. Larger counties with higher populations, like Wayne County, show significantly higher numbers of people affected, while other counties with smaller populations show lower totals. This can potentially mislead our understanding of the true disability burden across the state.

Therefore, percentage chart is a more reliable and insightful method for analyzing the prevalence of disabilities, especially when comparing counties of varying sizes. The total number of affected individuals can be misleading in areas with larger populations, making percentages a more accurate way to understand how widespread each disability is across different regions in Michigan. We can make this visualization even clearer to read using a 100% stacked bar chart.

In [16]:
# Create a 3x2 grid of subplots for visualizing different health categories
fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize=(20, 12))  # Define figure size
fig.suptitle("Health Data Analysis by Category in Top 5 Populated Counties (100% Stacked)", fontsize=16)  
# Set the overall title for the figure

# Flatten the 3x2 axes array into a 1D array for easier iteration
axes = axes.flatten()

# Loop through each category in the predefined list and create 100% stacked bar charts
for i, category in enumerate(categories):
    # Filter the dataset to include only data for the selected category and top 5 populated counties
    category_data = michigan_df[
        (michigan_df["Category"] == category) &  # Select specific health category
        (michigan_df["LocationName"].isin(top_counties))  # Restrict to top 5 counties
    ]

    # Group by 'Short_Question_Text' and 'LocationName', summing up 'Data_Value' (percentage data)
    category_grouped = (
        category_data.groupby(["Short_Question_Text", "LocationName"])["Data_Value"]
        .sum()
        .unstack()  # Convert 'LocationName' values into columns
        .fillna(0)  # Replace NaN values with 0
    )

    # Convert data to percentages to create a 100% stacked bar chart
    category_grouped = category_grouped.div(category_grouped.sum(axis=1), axis=0) * 100  

    # Plot the 100% stacked horizontal bar chart
    category_grouped.plot(kind="barh", stacked=True, colormap="icefire", ax=axes[i])

    # Set axis labels and titles
    axes[i].set_xlabel("Percentage Distribution")  # X-axis label
    axes[i].set_ylabel("Measure")  # Y-axis label
    axes[i].set_title(f"{category} by Percent Affected in Top 5 Counties (100% Stacked)")  # Set title

# Adjust the layout to prevent overlap of elements
plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.1, 1, 0.98])

# Display the figure
plt.show()

Genesee has a higher proportion of individuals experiencing complete tooth loss, while Oakland has lower rates of health insurance coverage, food stamp usage, and poorer general health. Wayne, on the other hand, has a lower proportion of people reporting social isolation. However, overall, the statistics remain relatively similar across the board.

Census ACS Poverty/ Income Data (2022) Merge¶

We are now going to pull poverty-related data from the U.S. Census Bureau's ACS API for all counties in the 2022 ACS 5-Year dataset.

In [17]:
# Load the CSV file
mapping = pd.read_csv(os.path.join(data_dir, "acs_poverty_md.csv"))  

# Extract the column names for the API request
columns = mapping["Column Name"].tolist()

# Construct the API URL
base_url = "https://api.census.gov/data/2022/acs/acs5/subject"
params = ",".join(columns)
query_url = f"{base_url}?get={params}&for=county:*"

# Call the API
response = requests.get(query_url)
if response.status_code != 200:
    print(f"Error: {response.status_code}, {response.text}")
else:  
    data = response.json()
    
    # Convert response to DataFrame
    census_df = pd.DataFrame(data[1:], columns=data[0])
    
    # Create a mapping from "Column Name" to "Label"
    column_mapping = dict(zip(mapping["Column Name"], mapping["Label"]))
    
    # Rename columns in census_df
    census_df.rename(columns=column_mapping, inplace=True)
    
    # Replace -999999999 values with 0
    census_df.replace("-999999999", "0", inplace=True)
    census_df.replace("-888888888", "0", inplace=True)
    census_df.replace("-666666666.0", "0", inplace=True)
    
    # Save to CSV
    census_df.to_csv(os.path.join(data_dir, "poverty_census_data.csv"), index=False)
    print("Data saved as poverty_census_data.csv")

We can see that all the numerical columns are stored as objects in the Census ACS dataset. Therefore, we need to convert these columns from object to int64 or float64 for proper numerical analysis.

In [21]:
# Extract the list of column labels from the 'Label' column in the mapping DataFrame.
label = mapping["Label"].tolist()

# Iterate through each column name in the extracted label list.
for column in label:
    # Check if the column is one of the specified columns that should be converted to float64.
    if column in ['Households<$10k', 'Households>$200k', 'BP_ Total%', 'BP_ African American%', 'BP_ American Indian/ Alaska Native%', 'BP_ Asian%', 'BP_ Hawaiian/ Pacific Islander%', 'BP_ Two or more races%', 'BP_ Other race%', 'BP_ Hispanic or Latino%', 'BP_ White%']:
        census_df[column] = census_df[column].astype('float64')  # Convert column to float64 type.
    
    # If the column is not 'Geography' or 'Geographic Area Name', convert it to int64.
    elif column not in ['Geography', 'Geographic Area Name']:
        census_df[column] = census_df[column].astype('int64')  # Convert column to int64 type.

In [34]:
def plot_health_data_by_category(df):
        # Define the list of categories to filter the data by
    categories = [
        'Health Outcomes', 'Disability', 'Health Status', 'Prevention', 
        'Health-Related Social Needs', 'Health Risk Behaviors'
    ]  # Select categories for analysis

    # Create a 2x3 grid of subplots to accommodate the six categories
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize=(18, 12))
    fig.suptitle("Health Data Analysis by Category", fontsize=16)

    # Flatten the axes array to make iteration easier
    axes = axes.flatten()

    # Loop through each category to create a bar chart for each
    for i, category in enumerate(categories):
        # Filter data for the current category, group by 'Health_Measure', 
        # sum 'Pop_Percent', and sort values in descending order
        category_data = (
            df[df['Category'] == category]
            .groupby('Health_Measure')['Pop_Percent']
            .sum()
            .sort_values(ascending=False)
        )
        
        # Create a bar plot for the current category
        sns.barplot(x=category_data.values, y=category_data.index, palette="crest", ax=axes[i])
        
        # Set the x-axis label and format the x-axis tick labels to prevent scientific notation
        axes[i].set_xlabel("Percent of People Affected")
        axes[i].ticklabel_format(style='plain', axis='x')
        
        # Set the y-axis label and title for the subplot
        axes[i].set_ylabel(category)
        axes[i].set_title(f"{category} by Percent of People Affected")
        
    # Adjust the layout to prevent overlap of titles and labels
    plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.1, 1, 0.98])

    # Display the plots
    plt.show()

We can see that in Isabella County, which has the highest poverty rate, the general health of the population appears to be poorer. People in this county are more likely to rely on health-related social services and face challenges such as food insecurity. Additionally, there is a greater prevalence of health risk behaviors in this county, likely as a result of the increased stress and economic hardships associated with higher poverty levels.

On the other hand, Livingston County, which has the lowest poverty rate, presents a different health challenge. Despite having fewer people living in poverty, the county shows a higher incidence of binge drinking, which is a significant health risk behavior.
